      "note": "Or: \"He is their patron [or \"master\"] today\": It should be borne in mind that the noun wali is derived from the verb waliya, which primarily signifies \"he was [or \"became\"] close [or \"near\", i.e., to someone or something]\". It is in this sense that the term wali is used in the Qur'an with reference to God's nearness to the believers (e.g., in 2:257 or 3:68), or their nearness to God (see 10:62 and the corresponding note 84). Similarly, the \"powers of evil\" (at-taghut) are spoken of in 2:257 as being \"near unto those who are bent on denying the truth (alladhina kafaru)\"."
